Staining dye PI targeting nucleic acids can permeate the cell but exclude living cells with intact plasma membranes [68]. We observed the Hoechst 33342/PI stain images by a fluorescence microscope. Treatment with the s-CGCDs showed clear red fluorescence in the broad range of E. coli and S. aureus cells, indicating severely broken integrity when compared with the m-CGCDs and l-CGCDs (Fig. 8
                        ). Further investigation of the bacterial membrane integrity was performed using the determination of released β-galactosidase. We speculate that the positively charged CGCDs increased the permeability of the E. coli plasma membrane so that the β-galactosidase in the cell is released from the cell, and it catalyzes the hydrolysis of ONPG (o-nitrophenyl-β-d-galactosidase) to produce the yellow ONP (o-nitrophenol) [26]. To test this hypothesis, we measured the absorbance at 420 nm, and the results are shown in Figure S14. As expected, the Abs420 intensity of cytosolic β-galactosidase released from E. coli showed size dependence compared to the untreated group, further confirming that greatly increasing cell permeability leads to irreversible membrane rupture [69]. It is conceivable that the nitrogen-containing group of CGCDs could interact on lipid bilayer membranes because of the electrostatic interactions of the amino group with the anionic sites of lipid phosphate [70]. The abundant amino/imine functional groups of antibacterial CGCD binding elicited a nonuniform surface charge on the membrane, causing leakage of low molecular weight compounds such as potassium ions and progressively altering the integrity of the membrane (perturbing the membrane composition) [71]. As illustrated in Fig. 9
                        B, the membrane zeta potential of E .coli increased from −50.9 to –22.8 mV after incubation with s-CGCDs for 30 min, which was significantly larger than that in the m-CGCD and l-CGCD groups under the same conditions. In addition, S. aureus, from −13.4 mV to −4.1 mV, showed the gradual insertion of cationic CGCDs into the cell wall. These results are in good accordance with the imaging outcomes shown in Fig. 8.
